description: From Middle English French, Frensch, Frensh, from Old English frencisc (“of the Franks, Frankish, French”), from Franca (“a Frank”). Compare Old High German Franko (“a Frank”), akin to Old English franca (“javelin, spear”), from the use of such weapons by the Franks.

verbs.description: french (third-person singular simple present frenches, present participle frenching, simple past and past participle frenched)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To prepare food by cutting it into strips.
(transitive) To kiss (another person) while inserting one’s tongue into the other person's mouth.
(cooking) To French trim; to stylishly expose bone by removing the fat and meat covering it (as done to a rack of lamb or bone-in rib-eye steak).
